  "shortBio": "Slagpups are ember-touched Riftlings of Ember Crater, four-footed and sure on uneven ground. Often mistaken for simple ember beasts, they are brave companions known for ember focus instincts and a quiet talent for reading unstable air. In Ember Crater, they favor Emberberry and soft routines.",
  "standardBio": "Slagpup, titled among keepers as “Cinderlane Scout,” carries restless warmth in every movement. Native to Ember Crater, the species kindles through ash and living coal, leaving traces that other Riftlings can follow like soft maps. Wild groups form loose bonds rather than rigid packs; a brave individual may become the emotional center of a small hearthline. They eat Emberberry eagerly and dislike food that smells of neglect or spoilage. Ancient keepers carved Slagpup silhouettes into travel stones, believing the species guided the lost. Modern hatcheries record them as reliable companions; their emotional intelligence above tool craft makes training feel like conversation. Their signature ability, Slagpup's Crater Claw, reflects a life shaped by Ember Crater more than by arena ambition. Their quiet is mistaken for emptiness. In truth they are listening harder than louder species. Young Slagpups practice Slagpup's Crater Claw as play long before they understand battle. Adults teach by demonstration: where to rest, what to avoid, how to share warmth or shade.",
  "fullLore": "Slagpups first condensed from residual hearthlight along the living edges of Ember Crater after early Rift fractures cooled into weather. Their eggs appear where ash and living coal gathers into stillness—never in the loudest danger, always in the pocket of calm beside it. Early surveyors mistook them for ambient phenomena until a Slagpup returned a dropped lantern, carefully, as if returning a promise.\n\nIn ancient eras, regional peoples treated Slagpups as omen-bearers rather than pets. Carvings show them walking ahead of caravans, pausing at unstable ground, and curling around children during ashfall or fog. The species was never “tamed” in the old sense; it chose. That choice culture survives in modern Riftkeeper etiquette: you do not yank a Slagpup into a bond. You invite, wait, and keep the invitation honest.\n\nModern history is quieter and more practical. Hatcheries map Slagpup care cycles with the same seriousness given to rare lines, because common does not mean shallow. Ember Crater still holds wild populations that trade soft greetings with passerby pets. After major Rift events, Slagpups often appear first at recovery centers—not as heroes, but as inventory clerks of comfort, counting who is cold, hungry, or afraid.\n\nNatural behavior is brave at the core and adaptable at the edges. They are four-footed and sure on uneven ground, companion-sized, easy to cradle, and communicate through body posture and scent marks. Socially, they prefer small trusted circles; strangers are assessed by scent, posture, and whether a keeper’s voice stays kind under stress. Intelligence presents as emotional intelligence above tool craft. They sleep in moss cups and prefer weather that matches their affinity’s comfort band.\n\nEcologically, Slagpups act as seed dispersers of calm within Ember Crater. Allies often include Cinderquill and Emberfox; rivalries with Tideotter and Cindercub are usually about nesting space or shiny refuse, not blood feuds. Predators are rare—most threats come from collapsing terrain and careless machines rather than jaws.\n\nCulture around them is affectionate and slightly superstitious. A collapsed survey team credited their escape to a Slagpup that chose the only stable ledge in a crumbling pass. Collectors prize unusual cosmetics, yet marketplace notes remind buyers that verified care history matters more than glitter. The common misunderstanding remains: Their quiet is mistaken for emptiness. In truth they are listening harder than louder species. The hidden truth keepers debate in soft rooms is simpler and stranger: When deeply bonded, a Slagpup shares short dream-images of places it has never physically visited.\n\nFrom egg to evolved form, their life story stays continuous. Eggs look like frosted pearls veined with ember light. Hatchlings are clumsy with sincerity; adults become specialists of place; evolved stages sharpen instinct without erasing childhood habits. Battle tendencies favor protective bursts, and evolution philosophy insists transformation should answer lived experience—not fashion.\n\nFor Riftkeepers, a Slagpup is a living chapter of Ember Crater. Feed it Emberberry, respect its brave tempo, and it will teach you the region’s quieter grammar: which winds lie, which stones remember, which silences are safe. Personal quests often begin with a shell symbol, a remembered scent, or a dream of a door that only opens when the bond is honest. That is the Slagpup bargain—not destiny sold at rarity price, but a life that continues because you showed up.",
